I wrote the following little Java program to test the behaviour of Duckling:
```java
package com.duckling.million;


import clojure.java.api.Clojure;
import clojure.lang.IFn;
import clojure.lang.LazySeq;
import clojure.lang.PersistentArrayMap;

public class DucklingTest {

    private static final IFn require = Clojure.var("clojure.core", "require");
    private static final IFn load = Clojure.var("duckling.core", "load!");
    private static final IFn parse = Clojure.var("duckling.core", "parse");

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        require.invoke(Clojure.read("duckling.core"));
        load.invoke();
        
        LazySeq results = (LazySeq) parse.invoke(
                "en$core", "0.1 million dollar", Clojure.read("[:amount-of-money]"));
        
        PersistentArrayMap result = (PersistentArrayMap) results.first();
        PersistentArrayMap value = (PersistentArrayMap) result.valAt(Clojure.read(":value"));
        
        System.out.printf("Type: %s\nValue: %s\nUnit: %s",
                value.valAt(Clojure.read(":type")),
                value.valAt(Clojure.read(":value")),
                value.valAt(Clojure.read(":unit")));
    }
}
```

Even with the latest version of Duckling (`0.4.24`) it prints out:
```
Type: value
Value: 1000000
Unit: $
```
I ran it on macOS Sierra with Oracle Java 1.8.0_141.

One important note: You raised the issue in the [reimplemented version of Duckling in Haskell](https://github.com/facebookincubator/duckling). However, this wrapper was developed for the [original Clojure version of Duckling](https://github.com/wit-ai/duckling_old).
The answer from the Duckling team in your linked issue sends a request against the new Haskell version.

