As pointed out by @wintersteiger the issue is likely the `is_int` variable.

```c++
    bool is_int;
    if (m_util.is_mod(arg2)) {
        std::swap(arg1, arg2);
        switch (kind) {
        case LE: kind = GE; break;
        case GE: kind = LE; break;
        case EQ: break;
        }
    }

    if (m_util.is_numeral(arg2, c, is_int) && is_int && 
        m_util.is_mod(arg1, t1, t2) && m_util.is_numeral(t2, b, is_int) && !b.is_zero()) {
```

Looking at the implementation of `m_util.is_numeral()` it takes a reference to `is_int` and assigns to it **if it returns true** so if we are assuming left to right evaluation order (which AFAIK can be assumed for the `&&` operator) then if `is_int` is evaluated in the branch it  **should have been already initialized**.

So I'm guessing either gcc is being overly aggressive when optimizing and reading `is_int` first or this is a false positive from valgrind.

Note if I initialize `is_int` the error from valgrind goes away.

